Intro

What is Pandas?

pandas is an open source, BSD-licensed library providing high-performance, easy-to-use data structures and data analysis tools for the Python programming language.

What is Plotly?

An interactive ploting library for Python

What is Seaborn?

A data visualization tool (usually static) built on top of matplotlib

Who is this for?

  • Novice Analysts
  • Med-Advanced Analysis Transitioning to Python
  • Someone who needs a refreser on the basics

Data Structures

  • A DataFrame is made of Series structures
    • A Series has a Row Names (index) and Column Names (columns) containing an array of the same value type (integer, float, string, etc..)

Data Munging

Data Types (dtypes)

  • Each column must have a single type
    • Object (strings, or any python object (like a list)
    • Floating (float)
    • Integer (int)
df.dtypes
country         object
description     object
designation     object
points           int64
price          float64
province        object
region_1        object
region_2        object
variety         object
winery          object
dtype: object
  • Note: Missing values are treated with a special NaN value, which is a float. This will convert your int dtypes to float if Pandas finds missing values in the column.

Finding Data

Loc Approach uses the indexes to locate the data you’re looking for.

df.loc[150929, 'country'] # Returns a string 
'Italy'
df.loc[150928:150930, 'country'] # Returns a series (of strings)
150928    France
150929     Italy
Name: country, dtype: object
df.loc[[150928, 150929], ['country', 'price']] # Returns a dataframe
country price
150928 France 52.0
150929 Italy 15.0

In many cases, we won’t know the index values that we’re looking for.

We’re often more interested in searching for specific values stored in one (or more) of the columns.

How would we do this?

Boolean Masking

Ex: I want to know which rows in the country column equal Italy

Step 1: Access the country Series object

Step 2: Set an equality condition

df['country'] == 'Italy'
0         False
1         False
2         False
3         False
4         False
          ...  
150925     True
150926    False
150927     True
150928    False
150929     True
Name: country, Length: 150930, dtype: bool

The result is a boolean series telling us which indexes equal “Italy”

We can transfer this operation into our .loc operation

italian_df = df.loc[(df['country'] == 'Italy')]
italian_df.head()
# This contains a new copy of our dataframe with only Italy countries

This is the most common way to search for data in Pandas.

We can combine boolean vectors using AND & and OR |

it_or_fr = (df['country'] == 'Italy') | (df['country'] == 'France')
# Show me wines from Italy OR France at or above the 95 percentile of the entire dataset
expensive_wine = df['price'] > df['price'].quantile(.95)
# Get me the rows where the row name is true for country italy or france and has expensive wine
df.loc[(it_or_fr) & (expensive_wine), ['country', 'variety', 'price', 'points']]

  • What if we wanted to know the average points per country?
  • We need a tool to group categories together and perform operations.

Data Visualization

Lets take the top 3 wine varieties and look at some visualization examples using plotly.

def select_by_top(_df, cat, n):
    return ( _df[cat]
            .value_counts()[:n]
            .index
            .tolist()
           ) 
vis_df = df.loc[df['variety'].isin(select_by_top(df,'variety', 3)),]
vis_df = vis_df.dropna()

Histograms and Bars

Preparing the data for counting

count_df = ( vis_df
            .groupby('variety')
            .size() # Count the amount of rows in the group
            .rename('count') # Name the series count
            .reset_index() # Set the group index as a column and create a new index
            )

Scatterplots

Plotting Relationships

  • Seaborn
  • Plotly
ax = sns.scatterplot(data=vis_df, x='price', y='points')
ax.set_title('Wine Price vs. Wine Rating')
plt.show()

fig = px.scatter(vis_df, x='price', y='points', title='Wine Price vs. Wine Rating')
fig.show()

This is looking a little cramped. Let’s try log scaling these plots.

  • Seaborn
  • Plotly
ax = sns.scatterplot(data=vis_df, x='price', y='points')
ax.set_xscale('log')
ax.set_title("Wine Price vs. Wine Rating")
plt.show()

fig = px.scatter(vis_df, x='price', y='points', title='Wine Price vs. Wine Rating', log_x=True)
fig.show()

Adding Color

  • Seaborn
  • Plotly
#Adding Color
ax = sns.scatterplot(data=vis_df, x='price', y='points', hue='variety')
ax.set_xscale('log')
ax.set_title("Wine Price vs. Wine Rating")
plt.show()

fig = px.scatter(vis_df, x='price', y='points', color='variety',title='Wine Price vs. Wine Rating', log_x=True, opacity=0.25)
fig.show()

Trends

Adding a Trendline

  • Seaborn
  • Plotly
fig = px.scatter(vis_df,
                 x='price',
                 y='points',
                 title='Wine Price vs. Wine Rating',
                 log_x=True,
                 opacity=0.2,
                 trendline='lowess')
fig.show()
ax = sns.regplot(data=vis_df, x='price', y='points', lowess=True, scatter_kws={'alpha': 0.1}, line_kws={'color': 'green'})
ax.set_xscale('log')
ax.set_title("Wine Price vs. Wine Rating")
plt.show()

Looks good! But how do these trends change by variety? What about province?

Faceting

Faceting allow for visualizing by a group.

We can combine everything we’ve learned thus far into a a single figure.

  • Seaborn
  • Plotly
g = ( sns.lmplot(
    data=vis_df, x='price', y='points', col='variety',
     row='province', lowess=True, line_kws={'color':'green'},
      scatter_kws={'alpha': 0.2}, facet_kws={'subplot_kws': {'xscale': 'log'}, 'margin_titles': True})
    )
g.set_titles(row_template = '{row_name}', col_template = '{col_name}')
plt.show()

fig = px.scatter(vis_df,
                 x='price',
                 y='points',
                 hover_data=['winery'],
                 facet_col='variety',
                 title='Wine Price vs. Wine Rating by Variety',
                 log_x=True,
                 opacity=0.2,
                 trendline='lowess',
                 facet_row='province',)
fig.for_each_annotation(lambda a: a.update(text=a.text.replace("province=", "")))# Cleaning up the row facets 
fig.show()

Seaborn Vs. Plotly Pro / Cons

Plotly Pros:

- Interactivity right out of the box. No assembly required!
- Great for dashboarding.
- Plotly express makes taking in pandas dataframes work well out of the box.

Plotly Cons:

- Newer and less mature than seaborn/matplotlib. May be harder to problem solve / debug.

Seaborn Pros:

- Matplotlib backend is more performant when plotting a lot of data.
- Matplotlib backend is very mature and it's fairly easy to google your way into the plot you want.

Seaborn Cons:

- Interactivity is more challenging to implement.
- API is complex and takes time to master when making customized plots.

Tips

  • Keep the number of intermediate DataFrames to a minimum
    • Having too many variables can confuse the reader and analyst. (Did I perform this operation on df85 or df86?)
    • Method chaining can help reduce the number of intermediate variables.
  • Check your work!
    • Its very possible to screw up your data without realizing you have.
    • Before you show your conclusions to stakeholders, perform some reasonable data checks.
  • Pick a data vis tool and stick to it.
    • Each takes a bit of time to master, and can be confusing to try and learn multiple data vis tools at once.
  • These tools have a lot of functionality and are complicated. Don’t be afraid to google if you can’t remember how to do something.
